# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: as-interface
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:as-interface/actuator] An **actuator** is a component of a machine that produces force, torque, or displacement, when an electrical, pneumatic or hydraulic input is supplied to it in a system (called an **actuating system**).
[src:as-interface/actuator] The effect is usually produced in a controlled way.
[src:as-interface/actuator] An actuator translates a stimulus such as an input signal into the required form of mechanical energy.
[src:as-interface/actuator] An actuator requires a control device (which provides control signal) and a source of energy.
[src:as-interface/actuator] The control signal is relatively low in energy and may be voltage, electric current, pneumatic, or hydraulic fluid pressure, or even human power.
[src:as-interface/actuator] In the electric, hydraulic, and pneumatic sense, it is a form of automation or automatic control.
[src:as-interface/actuator] The displacement achieved is commonly linear or rotational, as exemplified by linear motors and rotary motors, respectively.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Rotary motion is more natural for small machines making large displacements.
[src:as-interface/actuator] By means of a leadscrew, ball screw, or roller screw, rotary motion can be adapted to function as a linear actuator (which produces a linear motion, but is not a linear motor).
[src:as-interface/actuator] Another broad classification of actuators separates them into two types: incremental-drive actuators and continuous-drive actuators.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Stepper motors are one type of incremental-drive actuators.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Examples of continuous-drive actuators include DC torque motors, induction motors, hydraulic and pneumatic motors, and piston-cylinder drives (rams).
[src:as-interface/actuator] An actuator can be just a mechanism that is directly driven by the motions or forces of other parts of the system.
[src:as-interface/actuator] An example is the camshafts that drive the intake and exhaust valves in internal combustion engines, driven by the engine itself.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Another example is the mechanism that strikes the hours in a traditional grandfather clock or cuckoo clock.
[src:as-interface/actuator] A hydraulic actuator typically uses the pressure of a liquid (usually oil) to cause a piston to slide inside a hollow cylindrical tube into linear, rotary, or oscillatory motion.
[src:as-interface/actuator] In a *single acting* actuator the fluid pressure is applied to just one side of the piston, so that it applies useful force in only one direction.
[src:as-interface/actuator] The opposite motion may be affected by a spring, by gravity, or by other forces present in the system.
[src:as-interface/actuator] In a *double acting* actuator, the return stroke is driven by fluid pressure applied to the opposite side of the piston.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Since liquids are nearly impossible to compress, a hydraulic actuator can exert a large force.
[src:as-interface/actuator] The drawback of this approach is its limited acceleration.
[src:as-interface/actuator] They respond quickly to input changes, have little inertia, can operate continuously over a relatively large working range, and can hold their position without any significant energy input.
[src:as-interface/actuator] A hydraulic actuator can be used to displace the rack of a rack and pinion mechanism, causing the pinion to turn.
[src:as-interface/actuator] This arrangement is used, for example, to operate valves in pipelines and other industrial fluid transport installations.
[src:as-interface/actuator] A pneumatic actuator is similar to a hydraulic one but uses a gas (usually air) instead of a liquid.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Compared to hydraulic actuators, pneumatic ones are less complicated because they do not need pipes for the return and recycling of the working fluid.
[src:as-interface/actuator] On the other hand, they still need external infrastructure such as compressors, reservoirs, filters, and air treatment subsystems, which often makes them less convenient than electrical or electromechanical actuators.
[src:as-interface/actuator] In the first steam engines and in all steam locomotives, steam pressure is used to drive pneumatic actuators to produce a reciprocating motion, which is converted to rotary motion by some sort of crankshaft mechanism.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Since 1960, several actuator technologies have been developed.
[src:as-interface/actuator] An electric actuator typically uses an electric motor to generate torque, which is then converted into linear or rotary motion to drive a mechanical system.
[src:as-interface/actuator] An electromechanical actuator (EMA) uses mechanical means to convert the rotational force of an ordinary (rotary) electric motor into a linear movement.
[src:as-interface/actuator] The mechanism may be a toothed belt or a screw (either a ball or a lead screw or planetary roller screw).
[src:as-interface/actuator] The main advantages of electromechanical actuators are their relatively good level of accuracy with respect to pneumatics, their possible long lifecycle and the little maintenance effort required (might require grease).
[src:as-interface/actuator] It is possible to reach relatively high force, on the order of 100 kN.
[src:as-interface/actuator] The main limitation of these actuators are the reachable speed, the important dimensions and weight they require.
[src:as-interface/actuator] The main application of such actuators is mainly seen in health care devices and factory automation.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Another approach is an electrohydraulic actuator, where the electric motor remains the prime mover but provides torque to operate a hydraulic accumulator that is then used to transmit actuation force in much the same way that diesel engine/hydraulics are typically used in heavy equipment.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Electrical energy is used to actuate equipment such as multi-turn valves, or electric-powered construction and excavation equipment.
[src:as-interface/actuator] When used to control the flow of fluid through a valve, a brake is typically installed above the motor to prevent the fluid pressure from forcing open the valve.
[src:as-interface/actuator] If no brake is installed, the actuator gets activated to reclose the valve, which is slowly forced open again.
[src:as-interface/actuator] This sets up an oscillation (open, close, open ...) and the motor and actuator will eventually become damaged.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Electric rotary actuators use a rotary motor to turn the target part over a certain angle.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Rotary actuators can have up to a rotation of 360 degrees.
[src:as-interface/actuator] This allows it to differ from a linear motor as the linear is bound to a set distance compared to the rotary motor.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Rotary motors have the ability to be set at any given degree in a field making the device easier to set up still with durability and a set torque.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Rotary motors can be powered by 3 different techniques such as Electric, Fluid, or Manual.
[src:as-interface/actuator] However, Fluid powered rotary actuators have 5 sub-sections of actuators such as Scotch Yoke, Vane, Rack-and-Pinion, Helical, and Electrohydraulic.
[src:as-interface/actuator] All forms have their own specific design and use allowing the ability to choose multiple angles of degree.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Rotary actuators have numerous applications but are often found in hydraulic pressured devices and industries or tasks with motion control systems.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Rotary actuators are even used in robotic arms in industry lines.
[src:as-interface/actuator] A linear electric actuator uses a linear motor, which can be thought as a rotary electric motor which has been cut and unrolled.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Thus, instead of producing a rotational movement, it produces a linear force along their length.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Because it generally has lower friction losses than the alternatives, a linear electric actuator can last over a hundred million cycles.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Linear motors are divided in 3 basic categories: flat linear motor (classic), U-Channel linear motors and Tubular linear motors.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Linear motor technology is the best solution in the context of a low load (up to 30Kg) because it provides the highest level of speed, control and accuracy.
[src:as-interface/actuator] In fact, it represents the most desired and versatile technology.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Due to the limitations of pneumatics, the current electric actuator technology is a viable solution for specific industry applications and it has been successfully introduced in market segments such as the watchmaking, semiconductor and pharmaceutical industries (as high as 60% of the applications.
[src:as-interface/actuator] An actuator may be driven by heat through the expansion that most solid material exhibit when the temperature increases.
[src:as-interface/actuator] This principle is commonly used, for example, to operate electric switches in thermostats.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Typically, a (non-electronic) thermostat contains a strip with two layers of different metals, that will bend when heated.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Thermal actuators may also exploit the properties of shape-memory alloys.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Some actuators are driven by externally applied magnetic fields.
[src:as-interface/actuator] They typically contain parts made of ferromagnetic materials that are strongly attracted to each other when they are magnetized by the external field.
[src:as-interface/actuator] An example are the reed switches that may be used as door opening sensors in a building security system.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Alternatively, magnetic actuators can use magnetic shape-memory alloys.
[src:as-interface/actuator] A soft actuator is made of a flexible material that changes its shape in response to stimuli including mechanical, thermal, magnetic, and electrical.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Soft actuators mainly deal with the robotics of humans rather than industry which is what most of the actuators are used for.
[src:as-interface/actuator] For most actuators they are mechanically durable yet do not have an ability to adapt compared to soft actuators.
[src:as-interface/actuator] The soft actuators apply to mainly safety and healthcare for humans which is why they are able to adapt to environments by disassembling their parts.
[src:as-interface/actuator] The majority of the existing soft actuators are fabricated using multistep low yield processes such as micro-moulding, solid freeform fabrication, and mask lithography.
[src:as-interface/actuator] However, these methods require manual fabrication of devices, post processing/assembly, and lengthy iterations until maturity in the fabrication is achieved.
[src:as-interface/actuator] To avoid the tedious and time-consuming aspects of the current fabrication processes, researchers are exploring an appropriate manufacturing approach for effective fabrication of soft actuators.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Therefore, special soft systems that can be fabricated in a single step by rapid prototyping methods, such as 3D printing, are utilized to narrow the gap between the design and implementation of soft actuators, making the process faster, less expensive, and simpler.
[src:as-interface/actuator] They also enable incorporation of all actuator components into a single structure eliminating the need to use external joints, adhesives, and fasteners.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Shape memory polymer (SMP) actuators are the most similar to our muscles, providing a response to a range of stimuli such as light, electrical, magnetic, heat, pH, and moisture changes.
[src:as-interface/actuator] They have some deficiencies including fatigue and high response time that have been improved through the introduction of smart materials and combination of different materials by means of advanced fabrication technology.
[src:as-interface/actuator] The advent of 3D printers has made a new pathway for fabricating low-cost and fast response SMP actuators.
[src:as-interface/actuator] The process of receiving external stimuli like heat, moisture, electrical input, light or magnetic field by SMP is referred to as shape memory effect (SME).
[src:as-interface/actuator] SMP exhibits some rewarding features such a low density, high strain recovery, biocompatibility, and biodegradability.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Photopolymers or light activated polymers (LAP) are another type of SMP that are activated by light stimuli.
[src:as-interface/actuator] The LAP actuators can be controlled remotely with instant response and, without any physical contact, only with the variation of light frequency or intensity.
[src:as-interface/actuator] A need for soft, lightweight and biocompatible soft actuators in soft robotics has influenced researchers for devising pneumatic soft actuators because of their intrinsic compliance nature and ability to produce muscle tension.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Polymers such as dielectric elastomers (DE), ionic polymer–metal composites (IPMC), ionic electroactive polymers, polyelectrolyte gels, and gel-metal composites are common materials to form 3D layered structures that can be tailored to work as soft actuators.
[src:as-interface/actuator] EAP actuators are categorized as 3D printed soft actuators that respond to electrical excitation as deformation in their shape.
[src:as-interface/actuator] In engineering, actuators are frequently used as mechanisms to introduce motion, or to clamp an object so as to prevent motion.
[src:as-interface/actuator] In electronic engineering, actuators are a subdivision of transducers.
[src:as-interface/actuator] They are devices which transform an input signal (mainly an electrical signal) into some form of motion.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Rotary motors are primarily used when rotational motion is required, but can also be used for linear applications by transforming rotary motion into linear motion with a lead screw or similar mechanism.
[src:as-interface/actuator] On the other hand, some actuators are intrinsically linear, such as piezoelectric actuators.
[src:as-interface/actuator] In virtual instrumentation, actuators and sensors are the hardware complements of virtual instruments.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Performance metrics for actuators include speed, acceleration, and force (alternatively, angular speed, angular acceleration, and torque), as well as energy efficiency and considerations such as mass, volume, operating conditions, and durability, among others.
[src:as-interface/actuator] When considering force in actuators for applications, two main metrics should be considered.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Static load is the force capability of the actuator while not in motion.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Conversely, the dynamic load of the actuator is the force capability while in motion.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Speed should be considered primarily at a no-load pace, since the speed will invariably decrease as the load amount increases.
[src:as-interface/actuator] The rate the speed will decrease will directly correlate with the amount of force and the initial speed.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Actuators are commonly rated using the standard IP Code rating system.
[src:as-interface/actuator] Those that are rated for dangerous environments will have a higher IP rating than those for personal or common industrial use.
[src:as-interface/actuator] This will be determined by each individual manufacturer, depending on usage and quality.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] AS-Interface is an 'open' technology supported by a multitude of automation equipment vendors.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] The AS-Interface has been an international standard according to IEC 62026-2 since 1999.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] AS-Interface is a networking alternative to the hard wiring of field devices.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] It can be used as a partner network for higher level fieldbus networks such as Profibus, DeviceNet, Interbus and Industrial Ethernet, for whom it offers a low-cost remote I/O solution.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] It is used in automation applications, including conveyor control, packaging machines, process control valves, bottling plants, electrical distribution systems, airport baggage carousels, elevators, bottling lines and food production lines.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] AS-Interface provides a basis for Functional Safety in machinery safety/emergency stop applications.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] Safety devices communicating over AS-Interface follow all the normal AS-Interface data rules.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] The AS-Interface specification is managed by AS-International, a member funded non-profit organization located in Gelnhausen/Germany.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] Several international subsidiaries exist around the world.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] AS-Interface was developed during the late 1980s and early 1990s by a development partnership of 11 companies mostly known for their offering of industrial non-contact sensing devices like inductive sensors, photoelectric sensors, capacitive sensors and ultrasonic sensors.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] Once development was completed the consortium was resolved and a member organization, *AS-International*, was founded.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] The first operational system was shown at the 1994 Hanover fair.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] In 2018, a new technology step was presented at SPS IPC Drives in Nuremberg.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] ASi-5 was developed by well-known manufacturers of automation technology.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] The main application areas of the system are factory automation, process technology and home automation.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] The AS-Interface is a single-master system, this means a master device exchanges the input and output data with all configured devices.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] The transmission medium is an unshielded two-wire yellow flat cable.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] The cable is used for signal transmission and at the same time for power supply (30 V).
[src:as-interface/as-interface] The communication electronics and participants with low power requirements, like light beams, can be powered directly.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] Consumers with a higher energy requirement, such as valve terminals, can use a separate, usually black flat cable for power supply (30 V).
[src:as-interface/as-interface] The sensors or actuators are often connected via the so-called piercing technology.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] The insulation of the polarity profiled flat cable is pierced by means of two penetrating mandrels during assembly, this makes an easy and simple connection with reduced assembly efforts.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] Sensors and actuators that do not have an AS-Interface connection can be connected to the system via modules.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] For modules with penetration technology, the AS-Interface flat cable must be used.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] The topology of the AS-Interface networks is arbitrary.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] You can build lines, star, ring or tree structures.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] A telegram (message frame) consists of 4-bit user data.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] The master communicates with the participants with a serial transmission protocol.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] Each subscriber is assigned an address by an addressing device or via the master.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] A maximum of 31 (standard devices) or 62 (advanced devices) nodes can be connected.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] Each node can have up to four inputs and/or four outputs for actuators or sensors.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] This provides up to 124 (4 x 31 = 124) input and 124 outputs on a standard device network (nodes addressed 1-31) or 248 (4 x 62 = 248) inputs and 248 outputs on an advanced network (nodes addressed 1A - 31A and 1B - 31B ).
[src:as-interface/as-interface] The serial communication is modulated onto the power supply.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] Manchester coding is used for the communication.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] To address 62 participants, two cycles are necessary.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] The topology of the AS-Interface is arbitrary, but without a repeater or extender, the cable length must not exceed 100 m.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] Due to a special terminating resistor (a combination of resistive and capacitive load), however, it is possible to increase the maximum cable length up to 300 m.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] Diagnostic devices or masters with built-in diagnostics simplify network troubleshooting.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] Failed slaves can be easily replaced, the master automatically redirects them.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] Safety at Work is the concept of functional safety used in ASi-3 technology.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] This means that safety-related components such as emergency stop actuations, door interlocks or light grids can be used in the AS-Interface network.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] This is a different transmission protocol overlaid onto the regular ASi protocol on the same cable and requires a separate safety master such as Siemens ASiMon devices on which your safety devices are configured.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] AS-Interface can provide safety support up to SIL (Safety Integrity Level) 3 according to IEC 61508 as well as Performance Level e (PL e) according to EN ISO 13849-1.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] 16 bits are available for cyclic transmission using ASi-5.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] A cyclic transmission of up to 32 bytes per participant is possible.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] An acyclic parameter channel with up to 256 bytes is available for each device as well.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] ASi-5 is to provide a set of up to 1536 binary inputs and 1536 binary outputs per Ethernet address.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] 1.2 ms cycle time can be achieved by the system for up to 24 participants.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] This fast cycle time allows new fields of applications that were previously reserved for expensive network systems.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] 96 participants can be addressed in an ASi-5 network.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] These 96 devices then have a cycle time of 5 ms.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] Communication diagnostics describes the information about message transmission between the connected nodes and the master.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] The system continuously monitors the transmission quality of the messages from each device connected.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] This single channel diagnosis is available in the system.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] Disturbed transmission channels are redirected automatically.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] Device diagnostics provides information about the connected device.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] The available diagnostics data are determined by the device manufacturer.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] Diagnostic data can be transmitted via the acyclic services with a data width of up to 256 bytes.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] The ASi-5 system is open for the use of parameter interfaces such as e.g.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] IO-Link devices can be efficiently collected over long distances and could be integrated cyclically up to 32 bytes.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] 16 safe bits are available for safety-related switching devices, such as emergency stop, light curtains, safety switches and similar are available.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] It is possible to achieve Safety Integrity Level (SIL)3 Performance Level e according to IEC 13849 for functional safety.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] ASi-5 uses a novel communication method.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] The new ASi-5 technology allows the use of ASi-3 components together with components of the new ASi-5 technology on a common cable.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] If ASi-3 devices are to be used together with ASi-5 components, then in addition to the corresponding devices the use of a new ASi-3 / ASi-5 master is required.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] Old systems can be easily upgraded by new devices with additional functions.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] New systems can be installed on a cable using proven ASi-3 components and new ASi-5 devices.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] The AS-Interface is described in the international standard IEC 62026-2: 2015.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] AS-Interface products are certified by the AS-International Association e.V.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] Tests and certifications ensure that devices from different manufacturers work together.
[src:as-interface/as-interface] The concepts of functional safety at AS-Interface have been positively assessed by the TÜV (Technical Inspection Association) or the Institute for Occupational Safety of the German Social Accident Insurance and confirmed the fulfillment of the relevant safety standards.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Automation includes the use of various equipment and control systems such as machinery, processes in factories, boilers, and heat-treating ovens, switching on telephone networks, steering, stabilization of ships, aircraft and other applications and vehicles with reduced human intervention.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Examples range from a household thermostat controlling a boiler to a large industrial control system with tens of thousands of input measurements and output control signals.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] In the simplest type of an automatic control loop, a controller compares a measured value of a process with a desired set value and processes the resulting error signal to change some input to the process, in such a way that the process stays at its set point despite disturbances.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] This closed-loop control is an application of negative feedback to a system.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The mathematical basis of control theory began in the 18th century and advanced rapidly in the 20th.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The term *automation*, inspired by the earlier word *automatic* (coming from *automaton*), was not widely used before 1947, when Ford established an automation department.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] It was during this time that the industry was rapidly adopting feedback controllers, Technological advancements introduced in the 1930s revolutionized various industries significantly.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The World Bank's World Development Report of 2019 shows evidence that the new industries and jobs in the technology sector outweigh the economic effects of workers being displaced by automation.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Job losses and downward mobility blamed on automation have been cited as one of many factors in the resurgence of nationalist, protectionist and populist politics in the US, UK and France, among other countries since the 2010s.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] It was a preoccupation of the Greeks and Arabs (in the period between about 300 BC and about 1200 AD) to keep an accurate track of time.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] In Ptolemaic Egypt, about 270 BC, Ctesibius described a float regulator for a water clock, a device not unlike the ball and cock in a modern flush toilet.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] This was the earliest feedback-controlled mechanism.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The appearance of the mechanical clock in the 14th century made the water clock and its feedback control system obsolete.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The Persian Banū Mūsā brothers, in their *Book of Ingenious Devices* (850 AD), described a number of automatic controls.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Two-step level controls for fluids, a form of discontinuous variable structure controls, were developed by the Banu Musa brothers.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] They also described a feedback controller.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The design of feedback control systems up through the Industrial Revolution was by trial-and-error, together with a great deal of engineering intuition.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] It was not until the mid-19th century that the stability of feedback control systems was analyzed using mathematics, the formal language of automatic control theory.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was invented by Christiaan Huygens in the seventeenth century, and used to adjust the gap between millstones.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Another control mechanism was used to tent the sails of windmills.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Also in 1745, Jacques de Vaucanson invented the first automated loom.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Around 1800, Joseph Marie Jacquard created a punch-card system to program looms.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] In 1771 Richard Arkwright invented the first fully automated spinning mill driven by water power, known at the time as the water frame.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] An automatic flour mill was developed by Oliver Evans in 1785, making it the first completely automated industrial process.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Bunce of England in 1784 as part of a model steam crane.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was adopted by James Watt for use on a steam engine in 1788 after Watt's partner Boulton saw one at a flour mill Boulton & Watt were building.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The governor could not actually hold a set speed; the engine would assume a new constant speed in response to load changes.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The governor was able to handle smaller variations such as those caused by fluctuating heat load to the boiler.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Also, there was a tendency for oscillation whenever there was a speed change.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] As a consequence, engines equipped with this governor were not suitable for operations requiring constant speed, such as cotton spinning.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Several improvements to the governor, plus improvements to valve cut-off timing on the steam engine, made the engine suitable for most industrial uses before the end of the 19th century.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Advances in the steam engine stayed well ahead of science, both thermodynamics and control theory.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The governor received relatively little scientific attention until James Clerk Maxwell published a paper that established the beginning of a theoretical basis for understanding control theory.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Relay logic was introduced with factory electrification, which underwent rapid adaptation from 1900 through the 1920s.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Central electric power stations were also undergoing rapid growth and the operation of new high-pressure boilers, steam turbines and electrical substations created a great demand for instruments and controls.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Central control rooms became common in the 1920s, but as late as the early 1930s, most process controls were on-off.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Operators typically monitored charts drawn by recorders that plotted data from instruments.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] To make corrections, operators manually opened or closed valves or turned switches on or off.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Control rooms also used color-coded lights to send signals to workers in the plant to manually make certain changes.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The development of the electronic amplifier during the 1920s, which was important for long-distance telephony, required a higher signal-to-noise ratio, which was solved by negative feedback noise cancellation.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] This and other telephony applications contributed to the control theory.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] In the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flügge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic controls, which found military applications during the Second World War to fire control systems and aircraft navigation systems.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Controllers, which were able to make calculated changes in response to deviations from a set point rather than on-off control, began being introduced in the 1930s.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Controllers allowed manufacturing to continue showing productivity gains to offset the declining influence of factory electrification.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Factory productivity was greatly increased by electrification in the 1920s.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Alexander Field notes that spending on non-medical instruments increased significantly from 1929 to 1933 and remained strong thereafter.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The First and Second World Wars saw major advancements in the field of mass communication and signal processing.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Other key advances in automatic controls include differential equations, stability theory and system theory (1938), frequency domain analysis (1940), ship control (1950), and stochastic analysis (1941).
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] In 1959 Texaco's Port Arthur Refinery became the first chemical plant to use digital control.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Conversion of factories to digital control began to spread rapidly in the 1970s as the price of computer hardware fell.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The automatic telephone switchboard was introduced in 1892 along with dial telephones.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] By 1929, 31.9% of the Bell system was automatic.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Automatic telephone switching originally used vacuum tube amplifiers and electro-mechanical switches, which consumed a large amount of electricity.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Call volume eventually grew so fast that it was feared the telephone system would consume all electricity production, prompting Bell Labs to begin research on the transistor.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The logic performed by telephone switching relays was the inspiration for the digital computer.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The first commercially successful glass bottle-blowing machine was an automatic model introduced in 1905.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The machine, operated by a two-man crew working 12-hour shifts, could produce 17,280 bottles in 24 hours, compared to 2,880 bottles made by a crew of six men and boys working in a shop for a day.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The cost of making bottles by machine was 10 to 12 cents per gross compared to $1.80 per gross by the manual glassblowers and helpers.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives were developed using control theory.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives are used on different sections of a machine where a precise differential must be maintained between the sections.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] In steel rolling, the metal elongates as it passes through pairs of rollers, which must run at successively faster speeds.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] In paper making paper, the sheet shrinks as it passes around steam-heated drying arranged in groups, which must run at successively slower speeds.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The first application of a sectional electric drive was on a paper machine in 1919.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] One of the most important developments in the steel industry during the 20th century was continuous wide strip rolling, developed by Armco in 1928.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Before automation, many chemicals were made in batches.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] In 1930, with the widespread use of instruments and the emerging use of controllers, the founder of Dow Chemical Co. was advocating continuous production.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Self-acting machine tools that displaced hand dexterity so they could be operated by boys and unskilled laborers were developed by James Nasmyth in the 1840s.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Machine tools were automated with Numerical control (NC) using punched paper tape in the 1950s.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] This soon evolved into computerized numerical control (CNC).
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Today extensive automation is practiced in practically every type of manufacturing and assembly process.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Robots are especially useful in hazardous applications like automobile spray painting.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Robots are also used to assemble electronic circuit boards.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Automotive welding is done with robots and automatic welders are used in applications like pipelines.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] With the advent of the space age in 1957, controls design, particularly in the United States, turned away from the frequency-domain techniques of classical control theory and backed into the differential equation techniques of the late 19th century, which were couched in the time domain.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] During the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flugge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic control, which became widely used in hysteresis control systems such as navigation systems, fire-control systems, and electronics.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Through Flugge-Lotz and others, the modern era saw time-domain design for nonlinear systems (1961), navigation (1960), optimal control and estimation theory (1962), nonlinear control theory (1969), digital control and filtering theory (1974), and the personal computer (1983).
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Perhaps the most cited advantage of automation in industry is that it is associated with faster production and cheaper labor costs.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Another benefit could be that it replaces hard, physical, or monotonous work.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Additionally, tasks that take place in hazardous environments or that are otherwise beyond human capabilities can be done by machines, as machines can operate even under extreme temperatures or in atmospheres that are radioactive or toxic.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] They can also be maintained with simple quality checks.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] However, at the time being, not all tasks can be automated, and some tasks are more expensive to automate than others.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Initial costs of installing the machinery in factory settings are high, and failure to maintain a system could result in the loss of the product itself.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Automation primarily describes machines replacing human action, but it is also loosely associated with mechanization, machines replacing human labor.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The paradox of automation says that the more efficient the automated system, the more crucial the human contribution of the operators.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Humans are less involved, but their involvement becomes more critical.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Lisanne Bainbridge, a cognitive psychologist, identified these issues notably in her widely cited paper "Ironies of Automation." If an automated system has an error, it will multiply that error until it is fixed or shut down.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] A fatal example of this was Air France Flight 447, where a failure of automation put the pilots into a manual situation they were not prepared for.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Many roles for humans in industrial processes presently lie beyond the scope of automation.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Human-level pattern recognition, language comprehension, and language production ability are well beyond the capabilities of modern mechanical and computer systems (but see *Watson computer*).
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Tasks requiring subjective assessment or synthesis of complex sensory data, such as scents and sounds, as well as high-level tasks such as strategic planning, currently require human expertise.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] In many cases, the use of humans is more cost-effective than mechanical approaches even where the automation of industrial tasks is possible.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Therefore, algorithmic management as the digital rationalization of human labor instead of its substitution has emerged as an alternative technological strategy.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Overcoming these obstacles is a theorized path to post-scarcity economics.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] As of 2025-2026, real-world deployment of advanced robotics has revealed critical infrastructure limitations, such as "battery-life bottlenecks" (typically 2–4 hours of operation per charge) and the requirement for high-bandwidth Wi-Fi and specialized flooring for reliable function.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Additionally, robots continue to struggle with unpredictable human-made obstructions, which still necessitate human intervention to maintain operational flow.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Increased automation often causes workers to feel anxious about losing their jobs as technology renders their skills or experience unnecessary.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Early in the Industrial Revolution, when inventions like the steam engine were making some job categories expendable, workers forcefully resisted these changes.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Luddites, for instance, were English textile workers who protested the introduction of weaving machines by destroying them.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] More recently, some residents of Chandler, Arizona, have slashed tires and pelted rocks at a self-driving car, in protest over the cars' perceived threat to human safety and job prospects.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The relative anxiety about automation reflected in opinion polls seems to correlate closely with the strength of organized labor in that region or nation.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] According to one estimate, 47% of all current jobs in the US have the potential to be fully automated by 2033.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Furthermore, wages and educational attainment appear to be strongly negatively correlated with an occupation's risk of being automated.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Erik Brynjolfsson and Andrew McAfee argue that "there's never been a better time to be a worker with special skills or the right education, because these people can use technology to create and capture value.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Research by Carl Benedikt Frey and Michael Osborne of the Oxford Martin School argued that employees engaged in "tasks following well-defined procedures that can easily be performed by sophisticated algorithms" are at risk of displacement, and 47% of jobs in the US were at risk.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The study, released as a working paper in 2013 and published in 2017, predicted that automation would put low-paid physical occupations most at risk, by surveying a group of colleagues on their opinions.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] However, according to a study published in *McKinsey Quarterly* in 2015 the impact of computerization in most cases is not the replacement of employees but the automation of portions of the tasks they perform.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The methodology of the McKinsey study has been heavily criticized for being intransparent and relying on subjective assessments.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The methodology of Frey and Osborne has been subjected to criticism, as lacking evidence, historical awareness, or credible methodology.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Additionally, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) found that across the 21 OECD countries, 9% of jobs are automatable.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Based on a formula by Gilles Saint-Paul, an economist at Toulouse 1 University, the demand for unskilled human capital declines at a slower rate than the demand for skilled human capital increases.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] In the long run and for society as a whole it has led to cheaper products, lower average work hours, and new industries forming (i.e., robotics industries, computer industries, design industries).
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] These new industries provide many high salary skill-based jobs to the economy.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] By 2030, between 3 and 14 percent of the global workforce will be forced to switch job categories due to automation eliminating jobs in an entire sector.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] While the number of jobs lost to automation is often offset by jobs gained from technological advances, the same type of job loss is not the same one replaced and that leading to increasing unemployment in the lower-middle class.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] This occurs largely in the US and developed countries where technological advances contribute to higher demand for highly skilled labor but demand for middle-wage labor continues to fall.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Economists call this trend "income polarization" where unskilled labor wages are driven down and skilled labor is driven up and it is predicted to continue in developed economies.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Lights-out manufacturing is a production system with no human workers, to eliminate labor costs.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] It grew in popularity in the U.S. when General Motors in 1982 implemented humans "hands-off" manufacturing to "replace risk-averse bureaucracy with automation and robots".
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] However, the factory never reached full "lights out" status.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The costs of automation to the environment are different depending on the technology, product or engine automated.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] There are automated engines that consume more energy resources from the Earth in comparison with previous engines and vice versa.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Hazardous operations, such as oil refining, the manufacturing of industrial chemicals, and all forms of metal working, were always early contenders for automation.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The automation of vehicles could prove to have a substantial impact on the environment, although the nature of this impact could be beneficial or harmful depending on several factors.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Because automated vehicles are much less likely to get into accidents compared to human-driven vehicles, some precautions built into current models (such as anti-lock brakes or laminated glass) would not be required for self-driving versions.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Removal of these safety features reduces the weight of the vehicle, and coupled with more precise acceleration and braking, as well as fuel-efficient route mapping, can increase fuel economy and reduce emissions.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Despite this, some researchers theorize that an increase in the production of self-driving cars could lead to a boom in vehicle ownership and usage, which could potentially negate any environmental benefits of self-driving cars if they are used more frequently.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Automation of homes and home appliances is also thought to impact the environment.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] This study, along with others, indicated that the smart home's ability to monitor and adjust consumption levels would reduce unnecessary energy usage.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] However, some research suggests that smart homes might not be as efficient as non-automated homes.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] A more recent study has indicated that, while monitoring and adjusting consumption levels do decrease unnecessary energy use, this process requires monitoring systems that also consume an amount of energy.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The energy required to run these systems sometimes negates their benefits, resulting in little to no ecological benefit.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Another major shift in automation is the increased demand for flexibility and convertibility in manufacturing processes.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Manufacturers are increasingly demanding the ability to easily switch from manufacturing Product A to manufacturing Product B without having to completely rebuild the production lines.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Flexibility and distributed processes have led to the introduction of Automated Guided Vehicles with Natural Features Navigation.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Former analog-based instrumentation was replaced by digital equivalents which can be more accurate and flexible, and offer greater scope for more sophisticated configuration, parametrization, and operation.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] This was accompanied by the fieldbus revolution which provided a networked (i.e. a single cable) means of communicating between control systems and field-level instrumentation, eliminating hard-wiring.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Discrete manufacturing plants adopted these technologies fast.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The more conservative process industries with their longer plant life cycles have been slower to adopt and analog-based measurement and control still dominate.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The growing use of Industrial Ethernet on the factory floor is pushing these trends still further, enabling manufacturing plants to be integrated more tightly within the enterprise, via the internet if necessary.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Global competition has also increased demand for Reconfigurable Manufacturing Systems.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Engineers can now have numerical control over automated devices.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The result has been a rapidly expanding range of applications and human activities.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Computer-aided technologies (or CAx) now serve as the basis for mathematical and organizational tools used to create complex systems.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Notable examples of CAx include computer-aided design (CAD software) and computer-aided manufacturing (CAM software).
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The improved design, analysis, and manufacture of products enabled by CAx has been beneficial for industry.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Information technology, together with industrial machinery and processes, can assist in the design, implementation, and monitoring of control systems.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] One example of an industrial control system is a programmable logic controller (PLC).
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] PLCs are specialized hardened computers which are frequently used to synchronize the flow of inputs from (physical) sensors and events with the flow of outputs to actuators and events.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Human-machine interfaces (HMI) or computer human interfaces (CHI), formerly known as *man-machine interfaces*, are usually employed to communicate with PLCs and other computers.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Service personnel who monitor and control through HMIs can be called by different names.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] In the industrial process and manufacturing environments, they are called operators or something similar.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] In boiler houses and central utility departments, they are called *stationary engineers*.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Host simulation software (HSS) is a commonly used testing tool that is used to test the equipment software.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] HSS is used to test equipment performance concerning factory automation standards (timeouts, response time, processing time).
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Cognitive automation, as a subset of AI, is an emerging genus of automation enabled by cognitive computing.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Its primary concern is the automation of clerical tasks and workflows that consist of structuring unstructured data.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Cognitive automation relies on multiple disciplines: natural language processing, real-time computing, machine learning algorithms, big data analytics, and evidence-based learning.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Artificially intelligent computer-aided design (CAD) can use text-to-3D, image-to-3D, and video-to-3D to automate in 3D modeling.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] AI CAD libraries could also be developed using linked open data of schematics and diagrams.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Ai CAD assistants are used as tools to help streamline workflow.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Technologies like solar panels, wind turbines, and other renewable energy sources—together with smart grids, micro-grids, battery storage—can automate power production.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Many agricultural operations are automated with machinery and equipment to improve their diagnosis, decision-making and/or performing.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Agricultural automation can relieve the drudgery of agricultural work, improve the timeliness and precision of agricultural operations, raise productivity and resource-use efficiency, build resilience, and improve food quality and safety.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Increased productivity can free up labour, allowing agricultural households to spend more time elsewhere.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The technological evolution in agriculture has resulted in progressive shifts to digital equipment and robotics.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization using engine power automates the performance of agricultural operations such as ploughing and milking.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] With digital automation technologies, it also becomes possible to automate diagnosis and decision-making of agricultural operations.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] For example, autonomous crop robots can harvest and seed crops, while drones can gather information to help automate input application.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization has generally increased in recent years.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa is the only region where the adoption of motorized mechanization has stalled over the past decades.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Automation technologies are increasingly used for managing livestock, though evidence on adoption is lacking.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Adoption is likely mostly in Northern Europe, and likely almost absent in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Automated feeding machines for both cows and poultry also exist, but data and evidence regarding their adoption trends and drivers is likewise scarce.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Many supermarkets and even smaller stores are rapidly introducing self-checkout systems reducing the need for employing checkout workers.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] In the U.S., the retail industry employs 15.9 million people as of 2017 (around 1 in 9 Americans in the workforce).
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Globally, an estimated 192 million workers could be affected by automation according to research by Eurasia Group.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Online shopping could be considered a form of automated retail as the payment and checkout are through an automated online transaction processing system, with the share of online retail accounting jumping from 5.1% in 2011 to 8.3% in 2016.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] However, two-thirds of books, music, and films are now purchased online.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] In addition, automation and online shopping could reduce demands for shopping malls, and retail property, which in the United States is currently estimated to account for 31% of all commercial property or around 7 billion square feet (650 million square metres).
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Amazon has gained much of the growth in recent years for online shopping, accounting for half of the growth in online retail in 2016.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Other forms of automation can also be an integral part of online shopping, for example, the deployment of automated warehouse robotics such as that applied by Amazon using Kiva Systems.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The food retail industry has started to apply automation to the ordering process; McDonald's has introduced touch screen ordering and payment systems in many of its restaurants, reducing the need for as many cashier employees.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The University of Texas at Austin has introduced fully automated cafe retail locations.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Some cafes and restaurants have utilized mobile and tablet "apps" to make the ordering process more efficient by customers ordering and paying on their device.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Some restaurants have automated food delivery to tables of customers using a conveyor belt system.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The use of robots is sometimes employed to replace waiting staff.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Automation in construction is the combination of methods, processes, and systems that allow for greater machine autonomy in construction activities.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Construction automation may have multiple goals, including but not limited to, reducing jobsite injuries, decreasing activity completion times, and assisting with quality control and quality assurance.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Automated mining involves the removal of human labor from the mining process.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The mining industry is currently in the transition towards automation.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Currently, it can still require a large amount of human capital, particularly in the third world where labor costs are low so there is less incentive for increasing efficiency through automation.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) started the research and development of automated visual surveillance and monitoring (VSAM) program, between 1997 and 1999, and airborne video surveillance (AVS) programs, from 1998 to 2002.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Currently, there is a major effort underway in the vision community to develop a fully-automated tracking surveillance system.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Automated video surveillance monitors people and vehicles in real-time within a busy environment.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Existing automated surveillance systems are based on the environment they are primarily designed to observe, i.e., indoor, outdoor or airborne, the number of sensors that the automated system can handle and the mobility of sensors, i.e., stationary camera vs. mobile camera.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The purpose of a surveillance system is to record properties and trajectories of objects in a given area, generate warnings or notify the designated authorities in case of occurrence of particular events.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] As demands for safety and mobility have grown and technological possibilities have multiplied, interest in automation has grown.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Seeking to accelerate the development and introduction of fully automated vehicles and highways, the U.S.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Congress authorized more than $650 million over six years for intelligent transport systems (ITS) and demonstration projects in the 1991 *Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency Act* (ISTEA).
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Full automation commonly defined as requiring no control or very limited control by the driver; such automation would be accomplished through a combination of sensor, computer, and communications systems in vehicles and along the roadway.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Fully automated driving would, in theory, allow closer vehicle spacing and higher speeds, which could enhance traffic capacity in places where additional road building is physically impossible, politically unacceptable, or prohibitively expensive.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Automated controls also might enhance road safety by reducing the opportunity for driver error, which causes a large share of motor vehicle crashes.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Other potential benefits include improved air quality (as a result of more-efficient traffic flows), increased fuel economy, and spin-off technologies generated during research and development related to automated highway systems.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Automated waste collection trucks prevent the need for as many workers as well as easing the level of labor required to provide the service.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Business process automation (BPA) is the technology-enabled automation of complex business processes.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] It can help to streamline a business for simplicity, achieve digital transformation, increase service quality, improve service delivery or contain costs.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] BPA consists of integrating applications, restructuring labor resources and using software applications throughout the organization.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Robotic process automation (RPA; or RPAAI for self-guided RPA 2.0) is an emerging field within BPA and uses AI.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] BPAs can be implemented in a number of business areas including recruitment, marketing, sales and workflow.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Home automation (also called **domotics**) designates an emerging practice of increased automation of household appliances and features in residential dwellings, particularly through electronic means that allow for things impracticable, overly expensive or simply not possible in recent past decades.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The rise in the usage of home automation solutions has taken a turn reflecting the increased dependency of people on such automation solutions.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] However, the increased comfort that gets added through these automation solutions is remarkable.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Automation is essential for many scientific and clinical applications.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Therefore, automation has been extensively employed in laboratories.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] From as early as 1980 fully automated laboratories have already been working.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] However, automation has not become widespread in laboratories due to its high cost.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] This may change with the ability of integrating low-cost devices with standard laboratory equipment.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Autosamplers are common devices used in laboratory automation.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Logistics automation is the application of computer software or automated machinery to improve the efficiency of logistics operations.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Typically this refers to operations within a warehouse or distribution center, with broader tasks undertaken by supply chain engineering systems and enterprise resource planning systems.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Industrial automation deals primarily with the automation of manufacturing, quality control, and material handling processes.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] General-purpose controllers for industrial processes include programmable logic controllers, stand-alone I/O modules, and computers.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Industrial automation is to replace the human action and manual command-response activities with the use of mechanized equipment and logical programming commands.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] One trend is increased use of machine vision to provide automatic inspection and robot guidance functions, another is a continuing increase in the use of robots.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Industrial automation is simply required in industries.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The rise of industrial automation is directly tied to the "Fourth Industrial Revolution", which is better known now as Industry 4.0.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Originating from Germany, Industry 4.0 encompasses numerous devices, concepts, and machines, as well as the advancement of the industrial internet of things (IIoT).
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] An "Internet of Things is a seamless integration of diverse physical objects in the Internet through a virtual representation".
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] These new advancements have drawn attention to the world of automation and have shown ways for it to increase productivity and efficiency in machinery and manufacturing facilities.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 works with the IIoT and software/hardware to connect in a way that (through communication technologies) add enhancements and improve manufacturing processes.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Being able to create more advanced manufacturing is now possible with these new technologies.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] It opens up an improved manufacturing platform.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Implementation of systems such as SCADA is an example of software that takes place in industrial automation today.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] SCADA is a supervisory data collection software, just one of the many used in industrial automation.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 covers many areas in manufacturing.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Industrial robotics is a sub-branch in industrial automation that aids in various manufacturing processes.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Such manufacturing processes include machining, welding, painting, assembling and material handling to name a few.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Industrial robots use various mechanical, electrical as well as software systems to allow for high precision, accuracy and speed that far exceed any human performance.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The birth of industrial robots came shortly after World War II as the U.S. saw the need for a quicker way to produce industrial and consumer goods.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Servos, digital logic and solid-state electronics allowed engineers to build better and faster systems and over time these systems were improved and revised to the point where a single robot is capable of running 24 hours a day with little or no maintenance.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] In 1997, there were 700,000 industrial robots in use, the number has risen to 1.8M in 2017 In recent years, AI with robotics is also used in creating an automatic labeling solution, using robotic arms as the automatic label applicator, and AI for learning and detecting the products to be labelled.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Industrial automation incorporates programmable logic controllers in the manufacturing process.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) use a processing system which allows for variation of controls of inputs and outputs using simple programming.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] PLCs make use of programmable memory, storing instructions and functions like logic, sequencing, timing, counting, etc.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Using a logic-based language, a PLC can receive a variety of inputs and return a variety of logical outputs, the input devices being sensors and output devices being motors, valves, etc.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] PLCs are similar to computers, however, while computers are optimized for calculations, PLCs are optimized for control tasks and use in industrial environments.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] They are built so that only basic logic-based programming knowledge is needed and to handle vibrations, high temperatures, humidity, and noise.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The greatest advantage PLCs offer is their flexibility.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] With the same basic controllers, a PLC can operate a range of different control systems.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] PLCs make it unnecessary to rewire a system to change the control system.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] This flexibility leads to a cost-effective system for complex and varied control systems.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] PLCs can range from small "building brick" devices with tens of I/O in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with a count of thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] They can be designed for multiple arrangements of digital and analog inputs and outputs (I/O), extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Programs to control machine operation are typically stored in battery-backed-up or non-volatile memory.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] It was from the automotive industry in the United States that the PLC was born.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Before the PLC, control, sequencing, and safety interlock logic for manufacturing automobiles was mainly composed of relays, cam timers, drum sequencers, and dedicated closed-loop controllers.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Since these could number in the hundreds or even thousands, the process for updating such facilities for the yearly model change-over was very time-consuming and expensive, as electricians needed to individually rewire the relays to change their operational characteristics.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] When digital computers became available, being general-purpose programmable devices, they were soon applied to control sequential and combinatorial logic in industrial processes.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] However, these early computers required specialist programmers and stringent operating environmental control for temperature, cleanliness, and power quality.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] To meet these challenges, the PLC was developed with several key attributes.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] It would tolerate the shop-floor environment, it would support discrete (bit-form) input and output in an easily extensible manner, it would not require years of training to use, and it would permit its operation to be monitored.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Since many industrial processes have timescales easily addressed by millisecond response times, modern (fast, small, reliable) electronics greatly facilitate building reliable controllers, and performance could be traded off for reliability.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Agent-assisted automation refers to automation used by call center agents to handle customer inquiries.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The key benefit of agent-assisted automation is compliance and error-proofing.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] Agents are sometimes not fully trained or they forget or ignore key steps in the process.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] The use of automation ensures that what is supposed to happen on the call actually does, every time.
[src:as-interface/automation-p01] There are two basic types: desktop automation and automated voice solutions.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] Fundamentally, there are two types of control loop: *open-loop control* (feedforward), and *closed-loop control* (feedback).
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] One of the simplest types of control is *on-off* control.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] An example is a thermostat used on household appliances which either open or close an electrical contact.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] Sequence control, in which a programmed sequence of *discrete* operations is performed, often based on system logic that involves system states.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] An elevator control system is an example of sequence control.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] A proportional–integral–derivative controller (PID controller) is a control loop feedback mechanism (controller) widely used in industrial control systems.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] The theoretical understanding and application date from the 1920s, and they are implemented in nearly all analog control systems; originally in mechanical controllers, and then using discrete electronics and latterly in industrial process computers.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] Sequential control may be either to a fixed sequence or to a logical one that will perform different actions depending on various system states.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] An example of an adjustable but otherwise fixed sequence is a timer on a lawn sprinkler.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] States refer to the various conditions that can occur in a use or sequence scenario of the system.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] An example is an elevator, which uses logic based on the system state to perform certain actions in response to its state and operator input.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] For example, if the operator presses the floor n button, the system will respond depending on whether the elevator is stopped or moving, going up or down, or if the door is open or closed, and other conditions.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] Early development of sequential control was relay logic, by which electrical relays engage electrical contacts which either start or interrupt power to a device.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] Relays were first used in telegraph networks before being developed for controlling other devices, such as when starting and stopping industrial-sized electric motors or opening and closing solenoid valves.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] Using relays for control purposes allowed event-driven control, where actions could be triggered out of sequence, in response to external events.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] These were more flexible in their response than the rigid single-sequence cam timers.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] More complicated examples involved maintaining safe sequences for devices such as swing bridge controls, where a lock bolt needed to be disengaged before the bridge could be moved, and the lock bolt could not be released until the safety gates had already been closed.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] The total number of relays and cam timers can number into the hundreds or even thousands in some factories.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] Early programming techniques and languages were needed to make such systems manageable, one of the first being ladder logic, where diagrams of the interconnected relays resembled the rungs of a ladder.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] Special computers called programmable logic controllers were later designed to replace these collections of hardware with a single, more easily re-programmed unit.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] In a typical hard-wired motor start and stop circuit (called a *control circuit*) a motor is started by pushing a "Start" or "Run" button that activates a pair of electrical relays.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] The "lock-in" relay locks in contacts that keep the control circuit energized when the push-button is released.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] (The start button is a normally open contact and the stop button is a normally closed contact.) Another relay energizes a switch that powers the device that throws the motor starter switch (three sets of contacts for three-phase industrial power) in the main power circuit.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] Large motors use high voltage and experience high in-rush current, making speed important in making and breaking contact.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] This can be dangerous for personnel and property with manual switches.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] The "lock-in" contacts in the start circuit and the main power contacts for the motor are held engaged by their respective electromagnets until a "stop" or "off" button is pressed, which de-energizes the lock in relay.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] Commonly interlocks are added to a control circuit.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] Suppose that the motor in the example is powering machinery that has a critical need for lubrication.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] In this case, an interlock could be added to ensure that the oil pump is running before the motor starts.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] Timers, limit switches, and electric eyes are other common elements in control circuits.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] Solenoid valves are widely used on compressed air or hydraulic fluid for powering actuators on mechanical components.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] Computers can perform both sequential control and feedback control, and typically a single computer will do both in an industrial application.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) are a type of special-purpose microprocessor that replaced many hardware components such as timers and drum sequencers used in relay logic–type systems.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] General-purpose process control computers have increasingly replaced stand-alone controllers, with a single computer able to perform the operations of hundreds of controllers.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] Process control computers can process data from a network of PLCs, instruments, and controllers to implement typical (such as PID) control of many individual variables or, in some cases, to implement complex control algorithms using multiple inputs and mathematical manipulations.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] They can also analyze data and create real-time graphical displays for operators and run reports for operators, engineers, and management.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] Control of an automated teller machine (ATM) is an example of an interactive process in which a computer will perform a logic-derived response to a user selection based on information retrieved from a networked database.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] The ATM process has similarities with other online transaction processes.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] The different logical responses are called *scenarios*.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] Such processes are typically designed with the aid of use cases and flowcharts, which guide the writing of the software code.
[src:as-interface/automation-p02] The earliest feedback control mechanism was the water clock invented by Greek engineer Ctesibius (285–222 BC).
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] A **fieldbus** is a member of a family of industrial digital communication networks used for real-time distributed control.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Fieldbus profiles are standardized by the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) as IEC 61784/61158.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] A complex automated industrial system is typically structured in hierarchical levels as a distributed control system (DCS).
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In this hierarchy the upper levels for production managements are linked to the direct control level of programmable logic controllers (PLC) via a non-time-critical communications system (e.g.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The fieldbus links the PLCs of the direct control level to the components in the plant at the field level, such as sensors, actuators, electric motors, console lights, switches, valves and contactors.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] It also replaces the direct connections via current loops or digital I/O signals.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The requirements for a fieldbus are therefore time-critical and cost-sensitive.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Since the new millennium, a number of fieldbuses based on Real-time Ethernet have been established.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] These have the potential to replace traditional fieldbuses in the long term.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] A fieldbus is an industrial network system for real-time distributed control.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] It is a way to connect instruments in a manufacturing plant.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] A fieldbus works on a network structure which typically allows daisy-chain, star, ring, branch, and tree network topologies.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Previously, computers were connected using RS-232 (serial connections) by which only two devices could communicate.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] This reduces both the length of and total number of cables required.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Furthermore, since devices that communicate through a fieldbus require a microprocessor, multiple points are typically provided by the same device.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Some fieldbus devices now support control schemes such as PID control on the device-side instead of forcing the controller to do the processing.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The most important motivation to use a fieldbus in a distributed control system is to reduce the cost for installation and maintenance of the installation without losing the high availability and reliability of the automation system.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The goal is to use a two wire cable and simple configuration for field devices from different manufacturers.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Depending on the application, the number of sensors and actuators vary from hundreds in one machine up to several thousands distributed over a large plant.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The history of the fieldbus demonstrates how these goals have been approached over time.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Arguably the precursor field bus technology is HP-IB as described in IEEE 488 in 1975.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] "It became known as the General Purpose Interface Bus (GPIB), and became a de facto standard for automated and industrial instrument control".
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The GPIB has its main application in automated measurements with instruments from different manufacturers.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] It is a parallel bus with a cable and connector with 24 wires, limited to a maximal cable length of 20 metres.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The oldest commonly used field bus technology is Bitbus.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Bitbus was created by Intel Corporation to enhance use of Multibus systems in industrial systems by separating slow i/o functions from faster memory access.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In 1983, Intel created the 8044 Bitbus microcontroller by adding field bus firmware to its existing 8051 microcontroller.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Bitbus uses EIA-485 at the physical layer, with two twisted pairs - one for data and the other for clocking and signals.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Use of SDLC at the data link layer permits 250 nodes on one segment with a total distance of 13.2 km.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Bitbus has one master node and multiple slaves, with slaves only responding to requests from the master.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Bitbus does not define routing at the network layer.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The 8044 permits only a relatively small data packet (13 bytes), but embeds an efficient set of RAC (remote access and control) tasks and the ability to develop custom RAC tasks.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In 1990, the IEEE adopted Bitbus as the Microcontroller System Serial Control Bus (IEEE-1118).
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Today BITBUS is maintained by the BEUG - BITBUS European Users Group.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Office networks are not really suited for automation applications, as they lack the upper-bounded transmission delay.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] ARCNET, which was conceived as early as 1975 for office connectivity uses a token mechanism and therefore found later uses in industry.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The Manufacturing Automation Protocol (MAP) was an implementation of OSI-compliant protocols in automation technology initiated by General Motors in 1984.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] MAP became a LAN standardization proposal supported by many manufacturers and was mainly used in factory automation.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] MAP used the 10 Mbit/s IEEE 802.4 token bus as a transmission medium.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Due to its scope and complexity, MAP failed to make a big breakthrough.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] To reduce the complexity and reach faster processing with reduced resources the Enhanced Performance Architecture (EPA) MAP was developed in 1988.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] This MiniMap contains only levels 1, 2, and 7 of the Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) basic reference model.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] This shortcut was taken over by later fieldbus definitions.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The most important achievement of MAP is Manufacturing Message Specification (MMS), the application layer of MAP.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The Manufacturing Message Specification (MMS) is an international standard ISO 9506 dealing with an application protocol and services for transferring real time process data and supervisory control information between networked devices or computer applications published as a first version in 1986.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] It has been a model for many further developments in other industrial communication standardizations such as FMS for Profibus or SDO for CANopen.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] It is still in use as a possible application layer e.g. for power utility automation in the IEC 61850 standards.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In the field of manufacturing automation the requirements for a fieldbus are to support short reaction times with only a few bits or bytes to be transmitted over not more than some hundreds of meters.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In 1979 Modicon (now Schneider Electric) defined a serial bus to connect their programmable logic controllers (PLCs) called Modbus.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In its first version Modbus used a two wire cable with EIA 485 UART signals.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The protocol itself is very simple with a master/slave protocol and the number of data types are limited to those understood by PLCs at the time.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Nevertheless, Modbus is (with its Modbus-TCP version) still one of the most used industrial networks, mainly in the building automation field.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] A research project with the financial support of the German government defined in 1987 the fieldbus PROFIBUS based on the *Fieldbus Message Specification* (FMS).
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In practical applications, it proved too complicated to handle in the field.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In 1994 Siemens proposed a modified application layer with the name *Decentralized Periphery* (DP) which reached a good acceptance in the manufacturing industry.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] As of 2016, the Profibus is one of the most installed fieldbuses in the world and reached 60 million installed nodes in 2018.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In 1987 Phoenix Contact developed a serial bus to connect spatially distributed inputs and outputs to a centralized controller.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The controller sends one frame over a physical ring, which contains all input and output data.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The cable has 5 wires: besides the ground signal, two wires for the outgoing frame and two wires for the returning frame.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] With this cable is it possible to have the whole installation in a tree topology.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The INTERBUS was very successful in the manufacturing industry with more than 22,9 million devices installed in the field.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The Interbus joined the Profinet technology for Ethernet-based fieldbus Profinet and the INTERBUS is now maintained by the Profibus Nutzerorganisation e.V.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] During the 1980s, to solve communication problems between different control systems in cars, the German company Robert Bosch GmbH first developed the Controller Area Network (CAN).
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The concept of CAN was that every device can be connected by a single set of wires, and every device that is connected can freely exchange data with any other device.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] CAN soon migrated into the factory automation marketplace (with many others).
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In process automation traditionally most of the field transmitters are connected over a current loop with 4-20 mA to the controlling device.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] This allows not only to transmit the measured value with the level of the current, but also provide the required electrical power to the field device with just one two-wire cable of a length of more than a thousand meters.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] These systems are also installed in hazardous areas.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] According to NAMUR a fieldbus in these applications has to fulfill these requirements.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] A special standard for instrumentation, IEC/EN 60079-27, describes requirements for the Fieldbus Intrinsically Safe Concept (FISCO) for installations in zone 0, 1 or 2.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The FIP standard is based on a French initiative in 1982 to create a requirements analysis for a future field bus standard.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The study led to the European Eureka initiative for a field bus standard in June 1986 that included 13 partners.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The development group (réseaux locaux industriels) created the first proposal to be standardized in France.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The name of the FIP field bus was originally given as an abbreviation of the French "Flux d'Information vers le Processus" while later referring to FIP with the English name "Factory Instrumentation Protocol".
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] FIP has lost ground to Profibus which came to prevail the market in Europe in the following decade - the WorldFIP homepage has seen no press release since 2002.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The closest cousin of the FIP family can be found today in the Wire Train Bus for train coaches.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] However a specific subset of WorldFIP - known the FIPIO protocol - can be found widely in machine components.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus was developed over a period of many years by the International Society of Automation (ISA) as SP50.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus today enjoys a growing installed base in many heavy process applications such as refining, petrochemicals, power generation, and even food and beverage, pharmaceuticals, and nuclear applications.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Effective January 1, 2015, the Fieldbus Foundation has become part of the new FieldComm Group.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Profibus PA (process automation) is used for communication between measuring and process instruments, actuators and process control system or PLC/DCS in process engineering.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Profibus PA is a Profibus version with physical layer suitable for process automation, in which several segments (PA segments) with field instruments can be connected to Profibus DP via so-called couplers.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The two-wire bus cable of these segments takes over not only the communication, but also the power supply of the participants (MBP transmission technology).
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Another special feature of Profibus PA is the widely used device profile "PA Devices" (PA Profile), in which the most important functions of the field devices are standardized across manufacturers.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The BatiBUS defined in 1989 and used mainly in France, the Instabus extended to the European Installation Bus (EIB) and the European Home Systems Protocol (EHS) merged in 1999 to the Konnex) (KNX) standard EN 50090, (ISO/IEC 14543-3).
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In 2020 495 Member companies offer 8'000 products with KNX interfaces in 190 countries worldwide.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Going back to the 1980s, unlike other networks, LonWorks is the result of the work of computer scientists from Echelon Corporation.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In 1999 the communications protocol (then known as LonTalk) was submitted to ANSI and accepted as a standard for control networking (ANSI/CEA-709.1-B), in 2005 as EN 14908 (European building automation standard).
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The protocol is also one of several data link/physical layers of the BACnet ASHRAE/ANSI standard for building automation.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The BACnet standard was initially developed and is now maintained by the American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE) starting in 1987.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] BACnet is an American National Standard (ANSI) 135 since 1995, a European standard, a national standard in many countries, and global ISO Standard 16484 since 2003.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] BACnet has in 2017 a market share of 60% in building automation market.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Although fieldbus technology has been around since 1988, with the completion of the ISA S50.02 standard, the development of the international standard took many years.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In 1999, the IEC SC65C/WG6 standards committee met to resolve difference in the draft IEC fieldbus standard.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The result of this meeting was the initial form of the IEC 61158 standard with eight different protocol sets called "Types".
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] This form of standard was first developed for the European Common Market, concentrates less on commonality, and achieves its primary purpose—elimination of restraint of trade between nations.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Issues of commonality are now left to the international consortia that support each of the fieldbus standard types.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Almost as soon as it was approved, the IEC standards development work ceased and the committee was dissolved.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] A new IEC committee SC65C/MT-9 was formed to resolve the conflicts in form and substance within the more than 4000 pages of IEC 61158.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The work on the above protocol types is substantially complete.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] New protocols, such as for safety fieldbuses or real-time Ethernet fieldbuses are being accepted into the definition of the international fieldbus standard during a typical 5-year maintenance cycle.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In the 2008 version of the standard, the fieldbus types are reorganized into Communication Profile Families (CPFs).
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] There were many competing technologies for fieldbuses and the original hope for one single unified communications mechanism has not been realized.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] This should not be unexpected since fieldbus technology needs to be implemented differently in different applications; automotive fieldbuses are functionally different from process plant control fieldbuses.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In June 1999 the IEC's Committee of Action (CA) decided to take a new structure for the fieldbus standards beginning with a first edition valid at the January 1, 2000, in time for the new millennium: There is a large IEC 61158 standard, where all fieldbuses find their place.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The experts have decided that the structure of IEC 61158 is maintained according to different layers, divided into services and protocols.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The individual fieldbuses are incorporated into this structure as different types.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Each part still contains several thousand pages.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Therefore, these parts have been further subdivided into subparts.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The individual protocols have simply been numbered with a type.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Each protocol type thus has its own subpart if required.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In order to find the corresponding subpart of the individual parts of the IEC 61158 standard, one must know the corresponding protocol type for a specific family.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In the 2019 edition of IEC 61158 up to 26 different types of protocols are specified.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In IEC 61158 standardization, the use of brand names is avoided and replaced by dry technical terms and abbreviations.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] For example, Ethernet is replaced by the technically correct CSMA/CD or a reference to the corresponding ISO standard 8802.3.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] This is also the case with fieldbus names, they all are replaced by type numbers.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The reader will therefore never find a designation such as PROFIBUS or DeviceNet in the entire IEC 61158 fieldbus standard.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In the section Compliance to IEC 61784 a complete reference table is provided.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] It is clear that this collection of fieldbus standards in IEC 61158 is not suitable for implementation.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] It must be supplemented with instructions for use.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] These instructions show how and which parts of IEC 61158 can be assembled to a functioning system.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] This assembly instruction has been compiled subsequently as IEC 61784 fieldbus profiles.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The IEC 61784 Part 1 standard with the name *Profile sets for continuous and discrete manufacturing relative to fieldbus use in industrial control systems* lists all fieldbuses which are proposed by the national standardization bodies.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Swiftnet, which is widely used in aircraft construction (Boeing), was included in the first edition of the standard.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] This later proves to be a mistake and in the 2007 edition 2 this protocol was removed from the standard.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] At the same time, the CPF 8 CC-Link, the CPF 9 HART protocol and CPF 16 SERCOS are added.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In the edition 4 in 2014 the last fieldbus CPF 19 MECHATROLINK was included into the standard.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The edition 5 in 2019 was just a maintenance revision without any new profile added.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] See List of automation protocols for fieldbuses that are not included in this standard.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Already in edition 2 of the fieldbus profile first profiles based on Ethernet as physical layer are included.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] All this new developed Real-time Ethernet (RTE) protocols are compiled in IEC 61784 Part 2 as *Additional profiles for ISO/IEC 8802 3 based communication networks in real-time applications*.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The SERCOS solution is interesting in this context.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] This network from the field of axis control had its own standard IEC 61491.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] With the introduction of the Ethernet-based solution SERCOS III, this standard has been taken apart and the communication part is integrated in IEC 61158/61784.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The application part has been integrated together with other drive solutions into a special drive standard IEC 61800-7.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In 2010, a second edition was published to include CPF 17 RAPIEnet and CPF 18 SafetyNET p.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In the third edition (2014), the Industrial Ethernet (IE) version of CC-Link was added.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The two profile families CPF 20 ADS-net and CPF 19 FL-net were added to the fourth edition in 2019.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] For details about these RTEs see the article on Industrial Ethernet.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] For functional safety, different consortia have developed different protocols for safety applications up to Safety Integrity Level 3 (SIL) according to IEC 61508 or Performance Level "e" (PL) according to ISO 13849.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] What most solutions have in common is that they are based on a *Black Channel* and can therefore be transmitted via different fieldbuses and networks.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Depending on the actual profile the safety protocol does provide measures like counters, CRCs, echo, timeout, unique sender and receiver IDs or cross check.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] SERCOS does use the *CIP safety* protocol as well.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In the third edition in 2016 the last safety profile CPF 17 SafetyNET p was added.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] A new edition 4 is expected to be published in 2021.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The standard has now 9 different safety profiles.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] They are all included and referenced in the global compliance table in the next section.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The protocol families of each brand name are called Communication Profile Family and are abbreviated as CPF with a number.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Each protocol family can now define fieldbuses, real-time Ethernet solutions, installation rules and protocols for functional safety.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] These possible profile families are laid down in IEC 61784 and compiled in the following table.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] As an example, we will search for the standards for PROFIBUS-DP.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] This belongs to the CPF 3 family and has the profile CP 3/1.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In Table 5 we find that its protocol scope is defined in IEC 61784 Part 1.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The physical interface is defined in the common 61158-2 under type 3.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The installation regulations can be found in IEC 61784-5-3 in Appendix A.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] It can be combined with the FSCP3/1 as PROFIsafe, which is defined in the IEC 61784-3-3 standard.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] To avoid the manufacturer having to list all these standards explicitly, the reference to the profile is specified in the standard.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Discrete fieldbus networks are often referred to as "device networks".
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Already in the year 2000 the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) decided that a set of *controller-device interfaces* (CDIs) will be specified by the Technical Committee TC 121 *Low-voltage switchgear and controlgear* to cover the device networks.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The amount of cabling required is much lower in fieldbus than in 4–20 mA installations.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] This is because many devices share the same set of cables in a multi-dropped fashion rather than requiring a dedicated set of cables per device as in the case of 4–20 mA devices.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Moreover, several parameters can be communicated per device in a fieldbus network whereas only one parameter can be transmitted on a 4–20 mA connection.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] A fieldbus also provides a good foundation for the creation of a predictive and proactive maintenance strategy.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The diagnostics available from fieldbus devices can be used to address issues with devices before they become critical problems.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Despite each technology sharing the generic name of fieldbus the various fieldbuses are not readily interchangeable.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The differences between them are so profound that they cannot be easily connected to each other.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] To understand the differences among fieldbus standards, it is necessary to understand how fieldbus networks are designed.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] With reference to the OSI model, fieldbus standards are determined by the physical media of the cabling, and layers one, two and seven of the reference model.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] For each technology the physical medium and the physical layer standards fully describe, in detail, the implementation of bit timing, synchronization, encoding/decoding, band rate, bus length and the physical connection of the transceiver to the communication wires.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The data link layer standard is responsible for fully specifying how messages are assembled ready for transmission by the physical layer, error handling, message-filtering and bus arbitration and how these standards are to be implemented in hardware.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] The application layer standard, in general defines how the data communication layers are interfaced to the application that wishes to communicate.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] It describes message specifications, network management implementations and response to the request from the application of services.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Layers three to six are not described in fieldbus standards.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Different fieldbuses offer different sets of features and performance.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] It is difficult to make a general comparison of fieldbus performance because of fundamental differences in data transfer methodology.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] In the comparison table below it is simply noted if the fieldbus in question typically supports data update cycles of 1 millisecond or faster.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] As of 2008, in process control systems, the market is dominated by Foundation Fieldbus and Profibus PA.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Both technologies use the same physical layer (2-wire Manchester-encoded current modulation at 31.25 kHz) but are not interchangeable.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] As a general guide, applications which are controlled and monitored by programmable logic controllers (PLCs) tend towards PROFIBUS, and applications which are controlled and monitored by a digital/distributed control system (DCS) tend towards Foundation Fieldbus.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] PROFIBUS technology is made available through Profibus International with headquarters in Karlsruhe, Germany.
[src:as-interface/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus technology is owned and distributed by the Fieldbus Foundation of Austin, Texas.
[src:as-interface/sensor] A **sensor** is often defined as a device that receives and responds to a signal or stimulus.
[src:as-interface/sensor] The stimulus is the quantity, property, or condition that is sensed and converted into electrical signal.
[src:as-interface/sensor] In the broadest definition, a sensor is a device, module, machine, or subsystem that detects events or changes in its environment and sends the information to other electronics, frequently a computer processor.
[src:as-interface/sensor] Sensors like PIR sensor or touch sensor are used in everyday objects such as touch-sensitive elevator buttons (tactile sensor) and lamps which dim or brighten by touching the base, and in innumerable applications of which most people are never aware.
[src:as-interface/sensor] With advances in micromachinery and easy-to-use microcontroller platforms, the uses of sensors have expanded beyond the traditional fields of temperature, pressure and flow measurement, for example into MARG sensors.
[src:as-interface/sensor] Analog sensors such as potentiometers and force-sensing resistors are still widely used.
[src:as-interface/sensor] Their applications include manufacturing and machinery, airplanes and aerospace, cars, medicine, robotics and many other aspects of our day-to-day life.
[src:as-interface/sensor] There is a wide range of other sensors that measure chemical and physical properties of materials, including optical sensors for refractive index measurement, vibrational sensors for fluid viscosity measurement, and electro-chemical sensors for monitoring pH of fluids.
[src:as-interface/sensor] A sensor's sensitivity indicates how much its output changes when the input quantity it measures changes.
[src:as-interface/sensor] For instance, if the mercury in a thermometer moves 1 cm when the temperature changes by 1 °C, its sensitivity is 1 cm/°C (it is basically the slope dy/dx assuming a linear characteristic).
[src:as-interface/sensor] Some sensors can also affect what they measure; for instance, a room temperature thermometer inserted into a hot cup of liquid cools the liquid while the liquid heats the thermometer.
[src:as-interface/sensor] Sensors are usually designed to have a small effect on what is measured; making the sensor smaller often improves this and may introduce other advantages.
[src:as-interface/sensor] Technological progress allows for sensors to be manufactured in bulk on a microscopic scale as microsensors using MEMS technology.
[src:as-interface/sensor] In most cases, a microsensor reaches a significantly faster measurement time and higher sensitivity compared with macroscopic approaches.
[src:as-interface/sensor] Demand has increased for disposable sensors for short‐term monitoring or single‐shot measurements, due to their low cost and simpiclity of use.
[src:as-interface/sensor] Using this class of sensors, information can be obtained without the need for recalibration, and without potential contamination.
[src:as-interface/sensor] Most sensors have a linear transfer function.
[src:as-interface/sensor] The sensitivity is then defined as the ratio between the output signal and measured property.
[src:as-interface/sensor] For example, if a sensor measures temperature and has a voltage output, the sensitivity is constant with the units [V/K].
[src:as-interface/sensor] The sensitivity is the slope of the transfer function.
[src:as-interface/sensor] Converting the sensor's electrical output (for example V) to the measured units (for example K) requires dividing the electrical output by the slope (or multiplying by its reciprocal).
[src:as-interface/sensor] In addition, an offset is frequently added or subtracted.
[src:as-interface/sensor] For example, −40 must be added to the output if 0 V output corresponds to −40 C input.
[src:as-interface/sensor] For an analog sensor signal to be processed or used in digital equipment, it needs to be converted to a digital signal, using an analog-to-digital converter.
[src:as-interface/sensor] All these deviations can be classified as systematic errors or random errors.
[src:as-interface/sensor] Systematic errors can sometimes be compensated for by means of some kind of calibration strategy.
[src:as-interface/sensor] Noise is a random error that can be reduced by signal processing, such as filtering, usually at the expense of the dynamic behavior of the sensor.
[src:as-interface/sensor] The *sensor resolution* or *measurement resolution* is the smallest change that can be detected in the quantity that is being measured.
[src:as-interface/sensor] The resolution of a sensor with a digital output is usually the numerical resolution of the digital output.
[src:as-interface/sensor] The resolution is related to the precision with which the measurement is made, but they are not the same thing.
[src:as-interface/sensor] A sensor's accuracy may be considerably worse than its resolution.
[src:as-interface/sensor] A chemical sensor is a self-contained analytical device that can provide information about the chemical composition of its environment, that is, a liquid or a gas phase.
[src:as-interface/sensor] The information is provided in the form of a measurable physical signal that is correlated with the concentration of a certain chemical species (termed as analyte).
[src:as-interface/sensor] Two main steps are involved in the functioning of a chemical sensor, namely, recognition and transduction.
[src:as-interface/sensor] In the recognition step, analyte molecules interact selectively with receptor molecules or sites included in the structure of the recognition element of the sensor.
[src:as-interface/sensor] Consequently, a characteristic physical parameter varies and this variation is reported by means of an integrated transducer that generates the output signal.
[src:as-interface/sensor] A chemical sensor based on recognition material of biological nature is a biosensor.
[src:as-interface/sensor] However, as synthetic biomimetic materials are going to substitute to some extent recognition biomaterials, a sharp distinction between a biosensor and a standard chemical sensor is superfluous.
[src:as-interface/sensor] Typical biomimetic materials used in sensor development are molecularly imprinted polymers and aptamers.
[src:as-interface/sensor] A chemical sensor array is a sensor architecture with multiple sensor components that create a pattern for analyte detection from the additive responses of individual sensor components.
[src:as-interface/sensor] There exist several types of chemical sensor arrays including electronic, optical, acoustic wave, and potentiometric devices.
[src:as-interface/sensor] These chemical sensor arrays can employ multiple sensor types that are cross-reactive or tuned to sense specific analytes.
[src:as-interface/sensor] In biomedicine and biotechnology, sensors which detect analytes thanks to a biological component, such as cells, protein, nucleic acid or biomimetic polymers, are called biosensors.
[src:as-interface/sensor] Whereas a non-biological sensor, even organic (carbon chemistry), for biological analytes is referred to as sensor or nanosensor.
[src:as-interface/sensor] This terminology applies for both in-vitro and in vivo applications.
[src:as-interface/sensor] Neuromorphic sensors are sensors that physically mimic structures and functions of biological neural entities.
[src:as-interface/sensor] One example of this is the event camera.
[src:as-interface/sensor] The MOSFET invented at Bell Labs between 1955 and 1960, MOSFET sensors (MOS sensors) were later developed, and they have since been widely used to measure physical, chemical, biological and environmental parameters.
[src:as-interface/sensor] A number of MOSFET sensors have been developed, for measuring physical, chemical, biological, and environmental parameters.
[src:as-interface/sensor] The earliest MOSFET sensors include the open-gate field-effect transistor (OGFET) introduced by Johannessen in 1970, the ion-sensitive field-effect transistor (ISFET) invented by Piet Bergveld in 1970, the adsorption FET (ADFET) patented by P.F.
[src:as-interface/sensor] Cox in 1974, and a hydrogen-sensitive MOSFET demonstrated by I.
[src:as-interface/sensor] The ISFET is a special type of MOSFET with a gate at a certain distance, and where the metal gate is replaced by an ion-sensitive membrane, electrolyte solution and reference electrode.
[src:as-interface/sensor] The ISFET is widely used in biomedical applications, such as the detection of DNA hybridization, biomarker detection from blood, antibody detection, glucose measurement, pH sensing, and genetic technology.
[src:as-interface/sensor] By the early 2000s, BioFET types such as the DNA field-effect transistor (DNAFET), gene-modified FET (GenFET) and cell-potential BioFET (CPFET) had been developed.
[src:as-interface/sensor] MOS technology is the basis for modern image sensors, including the charge-coupled device (CCD) and the CMOS active-pixel sensor (CMOS sensor), used in digital imaging and digital cameras.
[src:as-interface/sensor] While researching the MOS process, they realized that an electric charge was the analogy of the magnetic bubble and that it could be stored on a tiny MOS capacitor.
[src:as-interface/sensor] As it was fairly straightforward to fabricate a series of MOS capacitors in a row, they connected a suitable voltage to them so that the charge could be stepped along from one to the next.
[src:as-interface/sensor] The CCD is a semiconductor circuit that was later used in the first digital video cameras for television broadcasting.
[src:as-interface/sensor] The MOS active-pixel sensor (APS) was developed by Tsutomu Nakamura at Olympus in 1985.
[src:as-interface/sensor] The CMOS active-pixel sensor was later developed by Eric Fossum and his team in the early 1990s.
[src:as-interface/sensor] MOS image sensors are widely used in optical mouse technology.
[src:as-interface/sensor] The first optical mouse, invented by Richard F.
[src:as-interface/sensor] Lyon at Xerox in 1980, used a 5 μm NMOS sensor chip.
[src:as-interface/sensor] Since the first commercial optical mouse, the IntelliMouse introduced in 1999, most optical mouse devices use CMOS sensors.
[src:as-interface/sensor] MOS gas detector sensors are used to detect carbon monoxide, sulfur dioxide, hydrogen sulfide, ammonia, and other gas substances.
[src:as-interface/sensor] Other MOS sensors include intelligent sensors and wireless sensor network (WSN) technology.
[src:as-interface/sensor] The typical modern CPUs, GPUs and SoCs are usually integrated electric sensors to detect chip temperatures, voltages and powers.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] In engineering, **master–slave** is a relationship between two systems in which one controls the other.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] In some cases, one master controls just one slave system, but in others, there are multiple slave systems controlled by the same master.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] Sometimes the master is a different kind of system than the slave, but sometimes there are multiple similar systems and one of them is designated the master in order to centralize external (i.e., user) control of the collection.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] Due to it being prone to being associated with slavery, the terminology is a subject of controversy and has been replaced with alternative terms in some cases.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] In photography, secondary, or slave, flash units are connected to a master unit to provide synchronized lighting.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] Parallel audio duplication often entails multiple recording with devices (i.e., for cassette tape or compact disc) linked together so that operating the controls of a master device triggers the same commands on slave devices.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] Railway locomotives operating in the same train (for example, to pull a load too heavy for a single locomotive) may be configured for master–slave operation with all but one of the locomotives controlled from the first.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] In a hydraulic system, a master cylinder is a control device that converts force into hydraulic pressure that drives movement in a slave cylinder at the other end of the hydraulic line.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] A common application is a vehicle brake system.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] A master clock provides time signals used to synchronize one or more slave clocks as part of a clock network.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] A slave clock receives and displays the time from a master, though it may be able to keep time itself if the master is not working.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] Computer bus protocols often use a master-slave relationship.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] For instance, a USB host manages access to the USB bus shared by any number of USB devices.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] A serial peripheral interface (SPI) bus typically has a single master controlling multiple slaves.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] I2C and I3C may even have multiple masters on a bus.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] Modbus also uses a master device to initiate connection requests to slave devices.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] An edge-triggered flip-flop can be created by arranging two gated latches in a master–slave configuration.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] It is so named because the master latch controls the slave latch's value and forces the slave latch to hold its value, as the slave latch always copies its new value from the master latch.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] In database replication, the master database is the authoritative source.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] The slave or replica database is controlled by the master database, which repeats its update commands (for example by way of event log) to the slave.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] Some databases implement so called *multi-master replication*, where a mix of writeable master nodes and readable nodes is used.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] These databases are used in scenarios where performance is an acceptable tradeoff for ACID properties, for example, non-mission-critical data, like suggesting similar purchases.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] The term *master* is used in some technology contexts that do not refer to a relationship of control.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] *Master* may be used to mean a copy that has more significance than other copies, in which case the term is an absolute concept, not a relationship.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] Sometimes the term *master–slave* is used in contexts that do not imply a controlling relationship.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] In source code management *master* may refer to the trunk.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] In disk imaging, the gold master is the version that will be released to manufacturing for duplication.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] A Parallel ATA (aka IDE) hard drive interface supports two hard drives on a cable, which are designated *master* and *slave*.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] The distinction is required by the interface even though neither drive has control or priority over the other.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] The *master–slave* terminology was first used in 1904.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] The terminology was used in 1988 for RFC 1059 and in 1997 for RFC 2136, related to the domain name system.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] Said hydraulic brakes for the automotive industry were patented in 1917 by Malcolm Loughead.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] The term *slave cylinder* was used in other patent applications, including one by Robert Esnault-Pelterie, published in 1919.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] Media analytics company Global Language Monitor placed *master/slave* first in their annual list of politically charged language for 2004.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] The Black Lives Matter movement in the United States sparked renewed discussion, and terminology changes occurred in 2020.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] Some argued, however, that terminology changes were superficial or performative activism.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] In 2003, after receiving a discrimination complaint from a county employee, the County of Los Angeles in California asked that manufacturers, suppliers and contractors stop using *master* and *slave* terminology on products.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] Following complaints, the County of Los Angeles issued a statement saying that the decision was "nothing more than a request".
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] In 2018, after a heated debate, developers of Python replaced the term.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] Depending on context, Python switched to *main*, *parent*, or *server* (in place of *master*), and *worker*, *child*, or *helper* (in place of *slave*).
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] The Linux kernel adopted a similar policy to use more specific terms in new code and documentation.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] In July 2018, Google's developer style guide was updated to include avoiding the term *master* in software documentation, especially in combination with *slave.* Instead, the guide recommends terms – when in combination – such as *primary/secondary* and *original/replica*.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] Many individual variants of master and slave are given.
[src:as-interface/slave-technology] In 2020, GitHub renamed the default *master* git branch to *main*.
